[4] UK (England): care home
Date: Tue 28 Apr 2020 14:10 BST
Source: The Scottish Sun [edited]
https://www.thescottishsun.co.uk/news/5539474/residents-die-care-home-essex/


Director Jenny Smith revealed almost 1/3 of residents have died at the 22-bed Westcliff Lodge Care Home in Westcliff-on-Sea, Essex, with staff now under mounting pressure.

She told BBC Breakfast: "We're all still adjusting and trying to process the loss. The loss and the pain and the devastation. "We have many people off sick as well with suspected [COVID-19], so we've been under tremendous pressure.

"There's so much fear among the staff because this is a virus that affects people of all ages, and that's a really primary difference really compared to normal influenza outbreaks."

The director said tests for the disease were not "timely enough" to stop the huge number of deaths.

She added: "I feel that's an issue perhaps beyond this country's control because we didn't have the same set-up, say, as Germany.

"Even more importantly, it perhaps wasn't reliable enough because some people were tested twice and had different results."

The care home, which has room for 22 residents, has been operating for the past 30 years.

New figures released today [28 Apr 2020] also showed COVID-19 care home deaths had trebled in the week leading up to [17 Apr 2020] from 1043 to 3096. It means 1/3 of all coronavirus deaths in England and Wales are now happening in care homes, the Office for National Statistics found.

But the Care Quality Commission (CQC) reported 4343 deaths of residents in homes between [10 and 24 Apr 2020] -- the 1st time such figures have been published by the body.

Pressure has been mounting on the Government to release the number of care home deaths and they have now pledged to provide more reliable data on the number of victims.

Some experts believe the true number of coronavirus deaths in care homes could be as high as 7500.

Responding to the latest figures, Cllr Ian Hudspeth, Chairman of the Local Government Association's Community Wellbeing Board, said: "It is truly shocking to see how many of the most elderly and vulnerable in our communities have died from this dreadful disease.

"Every death from this virus is a tragedy. This is being exacerbated by the fact some social care staff and other frontline workers still lack the necessary PPE to protect themselves and the people they care for from contracting coronavirus.

[Byline: Holly Christodoulou]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Care homes present a high at-risk population for COVID-19 infections, as the majority of residents are elderly and generally have underlying co-morbid conditions. If infected with SARS-CoV-2, the virus that causes COVID-19, residents are at increased risk of serious illness. Other infectious diseases such as influenza related outbreaks have been identified in the past from such facilities.

Facilities should educate residents, healthcare personnel (HCP), and visitors about COVID-19, by providing information about COVID-19 (including information about signs and symptoms) and strategies for managing stress and anxiety. Furthermore, HCP should be educated and trained on source control while in the facility with adherence to standard infection prevention and control measures, including hand hygiene and selection and use of personal protective equipment (PPE). Have HCP demonstrate competency with putting on and removing PPE instructions and monitor adherence by observing resident care activities. Sick leave policies should be reinforced, reminding HCP not to report to work when symptomatic. - Mod.UBA

HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of England, United Kingdom: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7281182,64484]

