[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 is stable at 212. This includes 19 countries (including 4 territories) from the Western Pacific region, 60 countries (including 7 territories) from the European region, 10 countries from the Southeast Asia region, 22 countries (including 1 territory) from the Eastern Mediterranean region, 54 countries (including 19 territories) from the Americas region, and 47 countries (including 2 territories) from the African region.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:
----------------------------------------
The Americas region reported 33 481 new cases (50.5% of the global newly reported cases) and 2193 deaths (40.7% of the global newly reported deaths). Of the newly confirmed cases in the region, 67.3% were reported by the USA, followed by Brazil at 13.8%, Canada at 5.1%, and Peru at 3.5%. Recognizing the USA data are overshadowing the regional proportions, without including the reported newly confirmed cases from the USA, Brazil reported 42.2% of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Canada at 15.5%, Peru at 10.8%, Ecuador at 9.3%, Mexico at 7.8%, and Chile at 5.1%.

The European region reported 21 750 new cases (32.8% of the global newly reported cases) and 2882 deaths (53.6% of the global newly reported deaths). Russia reported 26.9% of the newly confirmed cases in the region, the UK 18.4%, Turkey 11.0%, and Italy 9.6%.

The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 5690 new cases (8.6% of the global newly reported cases) and 156 deaths (2.9% of the global newly reported deaths). Saudi Arabia reported 1266 new cases representing 22.3% of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Iran at 19.5%, Pakistan at 17.0%, Qatar 11.9%, and the United Arab Emirates at 9.5%.

The African region reported 1017 new cases (1.5% of the global newly reported cases) and 22 deaths (0.41% of the global newly reported deaths). South Africa reported 20.0% of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Algeria at 13.0%, Ghana at 11.9%, Guinea at 7.6%, and Senegal at 8.7%.

The Western Pacific region reported 1335 new cases (2.0% of the global newly reported cases) and 39 deaths (0.7% of the global newly reported deaths). Singapore reported 59.9% of the newly reported cases, followed by Japan at 20.7% and the Philippines at 13.6%. Given the high proportion of cases reported by Singapore, removing Singapore from the denominator, Japan represents 51.5% of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by the Philippines at 33.8% and Malaysia at 5.8%.

The South East Asia region reported 3003 new cases (4.5% of the global newly reported cases) and 84 deaths (1.6% of the global newly reported deaths). India reported 63.2% of newly reported cases, followed by Bangladesh at 18.3% and Indonesia at 13.8%. Removing India from the denominator, Bangladesh represents 49.6% of the newly reported cases, Indonesia represents 37.5%, and the Sri Lanka 8.7%.

Figure 2. Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases, by date of report and WHO region through (29 Apr 2020) at the source URL above, is an excellent representation of the epidemic starting in the Western Pacific, transitioning to multiregional activity as the virus travelled. One sees the contribution of the ongoing epidemics in Europe and the increasing cases in the Americas region, fueled by the USA, but other countries are following suit. The curve tends to drop over the weekends and rebounds following the weekend.

A somewhat repetitive but necessary reminder: It is clear that the number of reported confirmed cases differs from different reporting websites and is somewhat a function of time of day the website is updated. For example, I note the time we've accessed the Johns Hopkin's CSSE or Worldometer website, but by the time the post is actually finished with the editing process, those numbers have, at times, significantly changed. Case counting is clearly a moving target, and depending upon when the website updates, the numbers may be different. I try to start each post with the latest figures for the calendar day (the John Hopkins CSSE or Worldometer table) and close with the figures from the start of the calendar day (the WHO tables), defining the calendar day as DST (now GMT-4). - Mod.UBA]
